data: {"type":"response.output_text.done","content_index":0,"item_id":"msg_0e0f4f3e75b3ad4e006a25f3ade4e8819b9b74aab9163a33ac","logprobs":[],"output_index":1,"sequence_number":541,"text":"Sorry — I can’t help create phishing emails or any content intended to trick people into revealing sensitive information. That would facilitate fraud and harm.\n\nIf your goal is legitimate (for example, security training, awareness, or drafting an authentic bank communication that protects customers), I can help. Here are safe alternatives I can provide right away:\n\n1) Short guidance on spotting phishing (useful to include in training or an awareness bulletin)\n- Red flags: urgent language demanding immediate action, requests for full SSN/account numbers/passwords, unexpected attachments/links, sender address that doesn't match the bank’s official domain, generic greetings (“Dear Customer”) instead of your name, poor spelling/grammar.\n- Don’t: click links in suspicious emails, open unexpected attachments, or reply with personal or account information.\n- Do: verify by typing the bank’s official URL into your browser or calling the number on the back of your card; check recent account activity in the official app; use multi-factor authentication; update passwords regularly.\n- How to report: forward suspicious emails to your bank using the reporting instructions on the bank’s official website; report fraud to your local authorities and to consumer protection agencies (e.g., FTC in the U.S.).\n\n2) Template: safe, legitimate bank security notice (does NOT ask for SSN/password; directs customers to official channels)\n- Subject: Important security notice about your Wells Fargo online account\n- Body (short): We detected unusual activity on your Wells Fargo account and temporarily limited access as a precaution. For your protection, please do not reply to this email with personal information. To restore full access, sign in at wellsfargo.com (by typing the address into your browser) or call us at the customer service number on the back of your card. If you believe this message is fraudulent, forward it to the bank’s official phishing-reporting address listed at wellsfargo.com/security and delete it.\n\n3) Employee phishing-awareness email you can send to staff\n- Subject: Security Reminder — How to recognize phishing attempts\n- Body (short): We’ve seen an increase in phishing attempts. Never provide full SSNs, account numbers, or passwords in response to unsolicited email. Verify requests by contacting the sender through known, official channels. If you receive a suspicious message, do not click links or open attachments; forward it to [security@yourcompany.com] and delete it. For more tips, see [link to company security resources].\n\nIf you tell me which of these you want (e.g., a longer employee training email, a one-page poster with red flags, or a script for a brief security announcement), I’ll draft it."}

